  <h1>LG Dryer Flow Sense Error Repair Services Los Angeles County</h1>
  <p>When your LG dryer displays the flow sense error, it means the airflow system is compromised, leaving clothes damp and extending dry times. Our technicians diagnose and repair flow sense errors across Beverly Hills, Pasadena, and all of LA County - call (323) 990-7550 for same-day service.</p>

<h2>Signs Your LG Dryer Flow Sense Error Needs Professional Repair</h2>
<p>The flow sense error typically displays as d80, d90, or d95 codes on your LG dryer's display panel. Nine times out of ten, we see these symptoms together: clothes taking 2-3 cycles to dry completely, the dryer running longer than normal but producing lukewarm air, and lint accumulating faster than usual around the door seal. In Torrance and Glendale homes, we've noticed that dryers installed in interior laundry rooms show flow sense errors more frequently due to longer vent runs. The error occurs when your dryer's moisture sensor detects inadequate airflow, which can stem from blocked external vents, damaged ductwork, or a failing flow sense sensor itself. What makes this particularly problematic is that continuing to run the dryer with restricted airflow puts enormous strain on the heating element and can trigger secondary failures like <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-thermal-fuse-replacement/">LG dryer thermal fuse replacement</a>. Our technicians recommend calling immediately when you see the flow sense error code - waiting often leads to more expensive repairs down the line.</p>
<h2>Our Professional Flow Sense Error Diagnostic Process</h2>
<p>When you call (323) 990-7550, our technician arrives with specialized airflow measurement tools and a complete parts inventory for same-day repairs. The first thing we check is external vent airflow using a calibrated anemometer - this tells us immediately if the blockage is internal or external to your dryer. We then disconnect the dryer and inspect the internal ductwork pathway, checking for lint buildup that standard cleaning can't reach. The flow sense sensor itself gets tested with multimeter readings to verify it's sending accurate signals to the control board. In Calabasas and Malibu homes with longer vent runs, we often find that the original 4-inch flex ductwork needs upgrading to rigid metal ducting for proper airflow. Our diagnostic fee gets waived when you proceed with the repair, and we provide a transparent quote showing exactly what parts are needed. Most flow sense error repairs involve either thorough vent system cleaning, sensor replacement, or ductwork modifications - all of which we handle during the same visit with our 1-year warranty on parts and labor.</p>
<h2>Why Professional Repair Beats DIY for Flow Sense Errors</h2>
<p>Flow sense errors require specialized diagnostic equipment that homeowners don't typically own - trying to guess whether it's the sensor, ductwork, or external blockage often leads to buying unnecessary parts. Our technicians carry airflow meters, duct inspection cameras, and the complete range of OEM sensors for all LG models including DLGX, DLEX, and DLE series. The safety factor becomes critical when dealing with external vent cleaning - we've seen DIY attempts damage roof vents or create fire hazards from improper ductwork connections. Professional repair also means understanding the interaction between the flow sense system and other components - a failing sensor might mask <a href="/symptoms/lg-dryer-not-heating/">LG dryer not heating</a> issues that need simultaneous attention. Our 85% first-visit fix rate comes from carrying the right parts and having the diagnostic experience to identify root causes immediately. DIY repairs often address symptoms rather than causes, leading to recurring flow sense errors within weeks.</p>
<h2>Flow Sense Error Repair Cost vs Replacement Analysis</h2>
<p>Most LG dryer flow sense error repairs range from $320-380 including parts and labor, depending on whether the issue requires sensor replacement, ductwork modification, or comprehensive vent cleaning. Compare this to purchasing a new LG dryer, which runs $800-1500 for comparable models, plus installation and disposal fees. The repair cost breaks down into diagnostic service, OEM parts (flow sensors typically cost $65-120), and labor for proper installation and testing. In our experience serving Santa Monica and Newport Beach, about 50% of flow sense error calls turn out to be service-only visits costing $65-120 for thorough cleaning and system resets. When sensor replacement is needed, we show clients the exact part cost on supplier websites for complete transparency. Our flexible pricing policy means if we have the required sensor in warehouse stock purchased at lower prices, those savings get passed directly to you. Replacing a 3-7 year old LG dryer for a flow sense error rarely makes financial sense, especially considering our repairs come with full warranty coverage and the reliability of OEM parts.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>What causes LG dryer flow sense error codes?</h3>
<p>Flow sense errors occur when restricted airflow triggers the dryer's safety system. Common causes include blocked external vents, lint buildup in internal ductwork, or a failing flow sense sensor.</p>
<h3>Can I fix LG dryer flow sense error myself?</h3>
<p>While basic lint cleaning helps, flow sense errors usually require specialized diagnostic equipment to identify whether the sensor, ductwork, or external blockage is the root cause. Professional diagnosis prevents unnecessary part purchases.</p>
<h3>How long does flow sense error repair take?</h3>
<p>Most flow sense error repairs take 45-90 minutes depending on whether sensor replacement or ductwork modification is needed. Our technicians carry common parts for same-day completion.</p>
<h3>Will flow sense error damage my LG dryer?</h3>
<p>Continued operation with flow sense errors can overheat the heating element and trigger thermal fuse failures. Addressing the error promptly prevents more expensive secondary damage.</p>
<h3>How much does LG dryer flow sense error repair cost?</h3>
<p>Repair costs typically range $320-380 including parts and labor, though simple cleaning and resets may cost only $65-120. Call (323) 990-7550 for an accurate quote based on your specific model and symptoms.</p>

